1
00:00:01,040 --> 00:00:05,799
99% of traders use time-based charts for their
technical analysis.

2
00:00:05,799 --> 00:00:10,490
But in recent years, another chart is becoming
more and more popular among day traders and

3
00:00:10,490 --> 00:00:14,730
scalpers, as it provides a different perspective
on trading than traditional time frames.

4
00:00:14,730 --> 00:00:19,110
In today’s video we’ll discuss about tick
charts, and I will explain how you should

5
00:00:19,110 --> 00:00:23,790
use them to find better entries in your trading
strategies.

6
00:00:23,790 --> 00:00:28,270
Tick charts are very simple to use and very
effective when measuring market momentum and

7
00:00:28,270 --> 00:00:29,610
trend strength.

8
00:00:29,610 --> 00:00:34,180
This type of charts is especially useful for
short-term traders, being often used in scalping

9
00:00:34,180 --> 00:00:35,720
and day trading strategies.

10
00:00:35,720 --> 00:00:37,680
So, what Are tick charts.

11
00:00:37,680 --> 00:00:42,660
Well, the bars on the tick charts are plotted
based on a particular number of transactions.

12
00:00:42,660 --> 00:00:49,470
For example, if we have a 200 tick chart,
each bar measures 200 trades per bar.

13
00:00:49,470 --> 00:00:54,180
After 200 trades are completed, a new bar
plots.

14
00:00:54,180 --> 00:01:00,329
Now very important, a single transaction could
include 1 contract, or 50 contracts, for example.

15
00:01:00,329 --> 00:01:04,479
The number of trades is what determines the
creation of a new tick on the chart, not the

16
00:01:04,479 --> 00:01:06,010
number of contracts.

17
00:01:06,010 --> 00:01:08,550
This is a very common confusion with tick
charts.

18
00:01:08,550 --> 00:01:12,250
So, tick charts are not measuring the true
number of contracts traded.

19
00:01:12,250 --> 00:01:16,960
It’s actually the number of transactions
made between traders, of varying contract

20
00:01:16,960 --> 00:01:18,890
sizes.

21
00:01:18,890 --> 00:01:21,310
With tick charts, the time element is removed.

22
00:01:21,310 --> 00:01:25,420
If you are trading on traditional charts,
you have limited options.

23
00:01:25,420 --> 00:01:28,830
With tick charts, you can backtest and choose
your own settings.

24
00:01:28,830 --> 00:01:34,119
Some prefer charts with 50, 100 or 200, 1000
or 2000 ticks.

25
00:01:34,119 --> 00:01:39,430
Others prefer to use Fibonacci numbers when
setting their number of ticks, like 21, 34,

26
00:01:39,430 --> 00:01:41,650
55, 89, 144 etc.

27
00:01:41,650 --> 00:01:45,520
Another approach would be to select the tick
number on your charts by comparing it to a

28
00:01:45,520 --> 00:01:46,800
time-based chart.

29
00:01:46,800 --> 00:01:50,951
For example, if you prefer day trading on
the 5-minute charts, you can choose a tick

30
00:01:50,951 --> 00:01:55,850
chart looking similar to that chart, like
200 ticks for example.

31
00:01:55,850 --> 00:02:00,860
If you prefer to scalp, charts with 50 or
100 ticks will probably suit you.

32
00:02:00,860 --> 00:02:05,610
For day trading, 500 or 1000 ticks are the
most common used.

33
00:02:05,610 --> 00:02:08,420
Of course, there is no best number of ticks
to trade with.

34
00:02:08,420 --> 00:02:13,209
You just have to test different settings and
select the one that suits you.

35
00:02:13,209 --> 00:02:15,050
Tick charts come with many advantages.

36
00:02:15,050 --> 00:02:16,050
1.

37
00:02:16,050 --> 00:02:19,909
Less Market Noise
As tick charts are transaction based and new

38
00:02:19,909 --> 00:02:24,829
bars are formed only when there have been
enough trades, the market noise is reduced.

39
00:02:24,829 --> 00:02:29,629
The noise is often represented by useless
candles, with no real value to the chart.

40
00:02:29,629 --> 00:02:33,799
Plus, the wicks of the candlestick often induce
traders into error.

41
00:02:33,799 --> 00:02:38,209
The higher the noise, the more difficult it
becomes to make intelligent decisions.

42
00:02:38,209 --> 00:02:44,519
You practically lose sight of what’s important
on the chart and focus on unimportant elements.

43
00:02:44,519 --> 00:02:49,109
The main advantage of a tick chart is that
compresses low-activity trading periods.

44
00:02:49,109 --> 00:02:55,180
On the time-based charts, you may see 30-40
useless candles, while the tick chart may

45
00:02:55,180 --> 00:02:58,610
offer you only 10-15 relevant ones.

46
00:02:58,610 --> 00:02:59,999
Look at the difference.

47
00:02:59,999 --> 00:03:03,290
We have these 2 trading range on the 5-minute
chart.

48
00:03:03,290 --> 00:03:06,329
And see the difference on a 200-ticks chart.

49
00:03:06,329 --> 00:03:09,329
The activity on the tick charts is more condensed.

50
00:03:09,329 --> 00:03:14,709
This may potentially enable you to get a clearer
picture of overall price action.

51
00:03:14,709 --> 00:03:16,239
2.

52
00:03:16,239 --> 00:03:21,129
Better Analysis of Volatility
With tick charts, you will see a new bar forming

53
00:03:21,129 --> 00:03:25,439
only when there have been enough trades completed
between buyers and sellers.

54
00:03:25,439 --> 00:03:28,999
In times of high activity, tick charts plot
more bars.

55
00:03:28,999 --> 00:03:31,300
This could signal an increased volatility.

56
00:03:31,300 --> 00:03:37,040
Usually, when the market opens, the volatility
increases and tick bars occur quickly.

57
00:03:37,040 --> 00:03:42,519
During the lunch hour, when the number of
trades decreases, the volatility decreases.

58
00:03:42,519 --> 00:03:45,519
This is often reflected in the activity on
the tick charts.

59
00:03:45,519 --> 00:03:49,780
During low activity periods, tick charts only
display a few bars.

60
00:03:49,780 --> 00:03:54,379
This is a better measurement of volatility
because on the time-based charts you’ll

61
00:03:54,379 --> 00:03:57,700
continue to see the less important candles.

62
00:03:57,700 --> 00:03:58,870
Look at this example.

63
00:03:58,870 --> 00:04:03,819
The first day was a low volatility day, with
few bars plotted on the tick chart.

64
00:04:03,819 --> 00:04:08,879
The second and third days had a higher volatility,
with large price movements and a higher number

65
00:04:08,879 --> 00:04:10,449
of bars.

66
00:04:10,449 --> 00:04:13,189
This represents an important information for
a trader.

67
00:04:13,189 --> 00:04:17,720
During the first day, a trader might skip
a signal occurring towards the end of the

68
00:04:17,720 --> 00:04:22,050
trading session, knowing that the market volatility
for that day was low.

69
00:04:22,050 --> 00:04:23,560
3.

70
00:04:23,560 --> 00:04:27,420
Clearer Swings
Without the accumulation of small candles

71
00:04:27,420 --> 00:04:32,530
like the ones on the time-based charts, tick
charts make it easier for the trader to spot

72
00:04:32,530 --> 00:04:33,530
swings.

73
00:04:33,530 --> 00:04:39,150
Also, while during high volatility periods
time-based charts may show only a long candle,

74
00:04:39,150 --> 00:04:41,390
tick charts show several smaller candles.

75
00:04:41,390 --> 00:04:46,640
In this way, tick charts provide traders with
more information about the recent market swings.

76
00:04:46,640 --> 00:04:52,090
When the volatility increases, a tick chart
shows more price waves and traders are able

77
00:04:52,090 --> 00:04:56,440
to identify proper support and resistance
levels.

78
00:04:56,440 --> 00:05:00,850
Here we have a 1-minute chart, showing the
market reaction after a non-farm payroll announcement,

79
00:05:00,850 --> 00:05:03,600
a powerful move in just a few minutes.

80
00:05:03,600 --> 00:05:09,590
On a 50-tick chart, the large movement printed
several bars, more exactly a 3-wave downtrend.

81
00:05:09,590 --> 00:05:13,930
A trader analyzing the tick chart had the
possibility to join the downward movement

82
00:05:13,930 --> 00:05:15,780
after a small pullback.

83
00:05:15,780 --> 00:05:22,200
The 1-min chart contained only 4 red candles,
all having wicks, to fool retail traders.

84
00:05:22,200 --> 00:05:23,600
4.

85
00:05:23,600 --> 00:05:28,280
Better Visualization of Breakouts
With tick charts, traders are able to spot

86
00:05:28,280 --> 00:05:31,310
breakouts faster than using a time-based chart.

87
00:05:31,310 --> 00:05:36,710
By using tick charts, traders can open a position
faster and, in most cases, at a better price

88
00:05:36,710 --> 00:05:37,710
level.

89
00:05:37,710 --> 00:05:38,710
Look at this example.

90
00:05:38,710 --> 00:05:43,120
Let’s say you try to scalp a new swing high
on the 1-min chart, waiting to trade an upside

91
00:05:43,120 --> 00:05:44,340
breakout.

92
00:05:44,340 --> 00:05:49,000
The breakout finally occurs, but you wait
for the price to retrace to the former resistance

93
00:05:49,000 --> 00:05:50,970
level and trade the retest.

94
00:05:50,970 --> 00:05:52,280
But the pullback never came.

95
00:05:52,280 --> 00:05:54,340
The market continued to go higher.

96
00:05:54,340 --> 00:05:58,250
Despite the fact that you anticipated the
breakout and lost a lot of time waiting for

97
00:05:58,250 --> 00:06:00,130
the setup, you missed a great trade.

98
00:06:00,130 --> 00:06:03,360
And, here’s the same setup, on a tick chart.

99
00:06:03,360 --> 00:06:07,750
We have the breakout and the chance to enter
long once the price retraced to the former

100
00:06:07,750 --> 00:06:10,190
resistance level, which became support.

101
00:06:10,190 --> 00:06:12,770
The tick chart allowed you to see the retest.

102
00:06:12,770 --> 00:06:16,871
The red candle which followed the breakout
candle was visible on the tick chart, but

103
00:06:16,871 --> 00:06:19,250
on the time-based chart wasn’t.

104
00:06:19,250 --> 00:06:25,170
This little aspect made the difference between
a successful trade and a wasted opportunity.

105
00:06:25,170 --> 00:06:27,000
5.

106
00:06:27,000 --> 00:06:32,680
More Accurate Signals from Technical Indicators
When using tick charts, traders receive more

107
00:06:32,680 --> 00:06:37,380
accurate signals from the technical indicators
they use, because the market noise is reduced,

108
00:06:37,380 --> 00:06:39,991
so the signals generated by indicators have
more relevance.

109
00:06:39,991 --> 00:06:45,840
Take a look at this 200-ticks chart, with
the Stochastic Oscillator added.

110
00:06:45,840 --> 00:06:49,980
Look at the divergence signal visible on the
indicator when using tick charts.

111
00:06:49,980 --> 00:06:53,380
Now, the same evolution, on a 5-minute chart.

112
00:06:53,380 --> 00:06:55,750
As you can see, no divergence is shown.

113
00:06:55,750 --> 00:07:00,050
Also, the choppiness of indicators is more
visible on time based charts.

114
00:07:00,050 --> 00:07:04,310
If you compare the signals offered by time
based chart with the ones generated by the

115
00:07:04,310 --> 00:07:07,740
tick chart you’ll see a slight difference.

116
00:07:07,740 --> 00:07:09,300
6.

117
00:07:09,300 --> 00:07:13,780
Better Measurement of Volume
A volume indicator plotted on a tick chart

118
00:07:13,780 --> 00:07:18,020
will offer you a better understanding of the
strength or weakness of a price move.

119
00:07:18,020 --> 00:07:22,500
The combination of tick charts and volume
could help traders to join strong moves and

120
00:07:22,500 --> 00:07:24,620
avoid moves that show weakness.

121
00:07:24,620 --> 00:07:29,330
The great thing about combining the use of
volume with tick charts is that each tick

122
00:07:29,330 --> 00:07:30,460
bar is equal.

123
00:07:30,460 --> 00:07:35,650
This allows you to see which price movements
are supported by high volume, and which aren’t.

124
00:07:35,650 --> 00:07:40,090
It essentially tells you which trends are
supported by smart money, and which ones are

125
00:07:40,090 --> 00:07:44,270
just retail money, making it likely to turn
over.

126
00:07:44,270 --> 00:07:45,780
7.

127
00:07:45,780 --> 00:07:50,590
Smaller and More Accurate Stop-Loss Orders
Tick charts can help you in placing better

128
00:07:50,590 --> 00:07:54,240
stop-loss orders and take-profit levels on
the chart.

129
00:07:54,240 --> 00:07:58,639
This is especially useful during periods of
high volatility and rapid price movements.

130
00:07:58,639 --> 00:08:04,490
For example, when a market moves rapidly,
the tick chart may plot multiple price swings

131
00:08:04,490 --> 00:08:07,870
which can be used for placing stops and profit
levels.

132
00:08:07,870 --> 00:08:13,410
By using a time-based chart, you can place
orders taking into account only one-two bars.

133
00:08:13,410 --> 00:08:18,460
Basicaly, when using time-based charts you
use slightly higher stop-loss orders, based

134
00:08:18,460 --> 00:08:20,730
on the swings on the respective chart.

135
00:08:20,730 --> 00:08:25,620
With tick charts, not only that you will be
able to see more waves and more entry points

136
00:08:25,620 --> 00:08:31,220
to set your orders, but you will also use
smaller stop-loss orders.

137
00:08:31,220 --> 00:08:32,220
Look at this chart.

138
00:08:32,220 --> 00:08:37,269
If you want to scalp this up move, a stop-loss
of 30 pips is required to enter a trade.

139
00:08:37,269 --> 00:08:40,539
That’s a big stop to be used on the 1-minutes
chart.

140
00:08:40,539 --> 00:08:43,669
Now look at the same situation on the 50-ticks
chart.

141
00:08:43,669 --> 00:08:47,769
Here you are able to buy the market at a much
better price.

142
00:08:47,769 --> 00:08:53,170
Also you can place the stop-loss order below
the recent swing, at 20 pips distance, compared

143
00:08:53,170 --> 00:08:56,850
to the 30 pips stop-loss order placed on the
M1 chart.

144
00:08:56,850 --> 00:09:01,730
When you scalp, this 10-pip difference is
huge, and gives you a safety net to manage

145
00:09:01,730 --> 00:09:03,010
your orders.

146
00:09:03,010 --> 00:09:07,000
Keep in mind that tick charts come with several
limitations.

147
00:09:07,000 --> 00:09:11,430
Tick charts can give you an advantage in day
trading, but they come at a cost as not many

148
00:09:11,430 --> 00:09:14,149
platforms are offering free tick data.

149
00:09:14,149 --> 00:09:18,980
Quality tick data can be really expensive
and not always is 100% accurate.

150
00:09:18,980 --> 00:09:24,259
Also, if you have the chance to compare tick
charts from different data feeds, you may

151
00:09:24,259 --> 00:09:26,209
notice that they differ.

152
00:09:26,209 --> 00:09:30,310
Some data feeds contain errors and not all
ticks are included.

153
00:09:30,310 --> 00:09:32,029
And this may affect your results.

154
00:09:32,029 --> 00:09:34,699
Sometimes drastically.

155
00:09:34,699 --> 00:09:39,860
Although it has many advantages over a candlestick
chart, a tick chart should be used as a complementary

156
00:09:39,860 --> 00:09:40,860
tool.

157
00:09:40,860 --> 00:09:44,800
Sure, you can use only tick charts in your
trading activity, but I recommend you to be

158
00:09:44,800 --> 00:09:49,050
conservative and try to combine them with
the classic time-based charts.

159
00:09:49,050 --> 00:09:51,779
This way, you have the full picture of the
market.

160
00:09:51,779 --> 00:09:56,430
A common technique used by traders is to spot
trends and support and resistance levels on

161
00:09:56,430 --> 00:10:00,410
the time-based charts and pinpoint the entries
on the tick charts.

162
00:10:00,410 --> 00:10:05,459
This way you reduce the market noise, determine
the volatility and take the signals on the

163
00:10:05,459 --> 00:10:11,079
tick charts while confirming the movement
with the help of time-based charts.

164
00:10:11,079 --> 00:10:15,009
As always, if you learned something new and
found value, leave us a like to show your

165
00:10:15,009 --> 00:10:19,360
support, subscribe to our channel and hit
the bell icon to stay notified when we upload

166
00:10:19,360 --> 00:10:20,360
new videos.

167
00:10:20,360 --> 00:10:21,419
Until next time.

